  _legacyStoryId: story_zombie_special
  storySegments:
  - storyId: story_zombie_official_seg1
    requiredItem: {fileID: 11400000, guid: dc4dd4bb1dc85eb448c9376aca1f71e2, type: 2}
    storySummary: "The moment the book was opened, memories unfolded like topographical
      maps: he had once been a surveyor dispatched by the imperial court to chart
      the land, traversing the four seas with his compass, measuring rods, and writing
      implements in tow. He had journeyed through mountain passes, salt marshes,
      desolate plains, and frontier outposts. Where others saw mere duty, he found
      an opportunity to \u2018know the world\u2019\u2014charting watercourses, the
      rise and fall of towns, strategic passes, while also recording local customs
      and the gaunt faces of famine years. This Travel Chronicle was his tribute
      to the court as the \u2018form of the realm,\u2019 yet equally his own testament
      to having existed, witnessed, and recorded."
  - storyId: story_zombie_official_seg2
    requiredItem: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 89a56ffcc89f1174e91e65140ca29d00, type: 2}
    storySummary: "That sugar-coated hawthorn had long since gone rancid and hardened,
      its red hue dulled, like a string of frozen sweetness from days gone by. Its
      appearance finally brought the other half of the story to light: he was perpetually
      away, his return uncertain. Each time he passed through the market, he would
      buy a string of sugar-coated hawthorn, thinking to bring it home to coax a
      smile from the children, and to tell his wife, \u2018I'm back.\u2019 Yet the
      surveyor's path was perpetually diverted, hurried, severed by the ravages of
      war\u2014the candied hawthorn would either dissolve in the rain or shatter
      beside his saddle. More often than not, he simply failed to return home. In
      the final days of the world, he remained stranded in another province, clutching
      only this string of \u2018undelivered sweetness.\u2019 As he drew his last
      breath, he gripped it tightly, as though grasping at an apology that had arrived
      far too late."
  dialogueConversationTitle: ZombieOfficial
  shortDescription: "Near the ruins of the post road, people have seen a zombie clad
    in official attire, its cuffs worn white, a broken surveyor's case hanging from
    its waist. Unlike other walking corpses that merely lunge and bite, this one
    mostly paces back and forth at the crossroads, as if confirming its direction
    or counting an invisible \u201Cmileage\u201D. It stares blankly at the ground,
    fingers repeatedly gesturing, as though measuring a road that no longer exists.
    If you draw near, you might hear indistinct words form in its throat: mountains
    and rivers, post stations, river crossings, boundary markers... all names from
    a bygone world."
